post_text: Cumberland County Schools congratulates two Glendale Acre Elementary School students on their winning entries in the 2019-2020 PTA Reflections Contest. Charlotte Barge won 2nd place in the Dance category with her entry titled “Reflection of Me." In the Literature category, Charlotte also received 3rd-place honors for her submission titled "I am many things on the inside" and Brandon Whitley was awarded 2nd-place honors for his submission titled "What we all should have is kindness."

post_text: Operation Smooth Start is all about helping everyone ease into the new school year. We will collaboratively work through any issues that may arise. During the first 10 days of school, we will set the stage for student success. Live student-teacher interactions will occur beginning on the first day of school, but no high-stakes assignments will be made before August 31. We want to ensure that each student is able to pick up the necessary materials, understand expectations and address any questions. This is a new normal, but we will learn and grow together. This is going to be a great school year! Learn more at: https://bit.ly/3iZd2Lh. #CCSSmoothStart

post_text: On August 3, 2020, Governor Roy Cooper announced the appointment of Attorney Nick Sojka to the Interstate Compact on Educational Opportunities for Military Children. Mr. Sojka serves as Board Attorney for the Cumberland County Board of Education and Cumberland County Schools, and he is also a member of the Governor's Commission on Access to Sound Basic Education. Mr. Sojka has represented public school systems in the Cape Fear region since 1993.

Wear your Face Covering Correctly:
* Wash your hands before putting on your face covering
* Put it over your nose and mouth and secure it under your chin
* Try to fit it snugly against the sides of your face
* Make sure you can breathe easily

post_text: The safety of students, staff and families is the district’s top priority. As district officials prepare for reopening schools, several health and safety precautions are being put in place. Personal protective equipment (PPE) will be available, 6ft markings are being placed on floors and sidewalks, sneeze guards are being installed at reception areas, and masks will be available for students, as appropriate, and staff members. In preparation for any remote instruction, an additional 10,000 devices have been ordered. To view CCS' COVID-19 Family Guidance for a Healthy Return and learn more about health and safety precautions for the 2020-2021 school year, visit www.reentry.ccs.k12.nc.us.

post_text: As the COVID-19 pandemic looms and the start of a new school year approaches on August 17, we are giving you the chance to decide how your child will be educated during the 2020-2021 school year based on what’s best for your family. This morning, our Board of Education approved three plans for the opening of schools: Plan A - Traditional Face-to-Face Learning with Minimal Social Distancing; Plan B - Blended-Remote and Face-to-Face Learning; and Plan C - Total Remote Learning. We understand that Governor Cooper will give his official guidance for reopening school next week. Please know that based on his announcement, our proposed plans are subject to change. But, if the Governor selects Plan B -- Blended-Remote and Face-to-Face Learning -- it will require you to choose one of three options for your child's learning experience next year. Detailed information about the options are on the CCS Website. Our re-entry enrollment period, where you will decide what option is best for your child, is open from July 13-19. Learn more about the options at www.reentry.ccs.k12.nc.us.

post_text: CCS’ Office of Indian Education recently honored graduating American Indian seniors during a special drive-thru Eagle Feather Ceremony in the parking lot of the Educational Resource Center. Each senior received an eagle feather in a keepsake box. According to the Office of Indian Education, the feather symbolizes trust, honor, strength, wisdom, power, and freedom and is deeply revered as a sign of high honor. In Native American culture, it is believed that all things possess an inherent virtue, power, and wisdom. The feather, for example, is a powerful symbol that signifies honor and a connection between the owner, the Creator, and the bird from which the feather came.
